Title: The Lamp Room
Credit: written by
Author: brehon
Source: generated from a metaphor DAG

# ACT ONE

INT. LAMP ROOM - DAWN

He turns the crank thirty-three times. The gears engage.

INT. LAMP ROOM - NOON

He wipes the outer lens with a dry cloth. No streaks remain.

INT. KEEPER'S QUARTERS - AFTERNOON

He writes in the log: 'Sea clear. Light burning steady.'

EXT. CLIFF PATH - DUSK

Three flashes from the horizon. He returns two.

# ACT TWO

INT. LAMP ROOM - NIGHT

He peels back a strip of yellow wax from the base of the lamp housing.

INT. KEEPER'S QUARTERS - NIGHT

He holds the blueprint. The arrow points seaward, not inland.

INT. LAMP ROOM - NIGHT

He looks through the lens at night. A reef glints under moonlight.

EXT. DOCK - DAWN

CAPTAIN
(quiet, tired)
That light's been drawing them onto the rocks for twenty years.

INT. LAMP ROOM - NIGHT

He melts a new strip of wax and presses it into place.

# ACT THREE

INT. LAMP ROOM - NIGHT

The lamp sputters. The glass cools.

INT. LAMP ROOM - NIGHT

He places the crank handle on the workbench. It does not move.

INT. KEEPER'S QUARTERS - DAWN

He writes: 'Light out. No ships seen.'

EXT. LIGHTHOUSE - DAWN

He opens the door. The wind pushes it wide. He steps out.
